<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="86" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d86">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5531/372</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chief of the Belgian Commercial
                                    Delegation</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Forthomme</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-21">February 21, 1935</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: Mr. Camu has just
                                had an interview with officers of the Department of Agriculture, and
                                it seems from this interview that if Belgium wishes to obtain the
                                authorization to import bulbs packed in sand into the United States,
                                a formal request to this effect must be sent to the Department in
                                question.</p>
                            <p>Since this is one of the points considered in the Belgian memorandum
                                of November 12, 1934,<note n="21" xml:id="d86fn21"><ref target="frus1934v02#pg_627"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                                        p. 627</ref>.</note> I have the honor of asking you kindly
                                to forward this request, in my name, to your honorable colleague the
                                Secretary of Agriculture.</p>
                            <p>I have heard that this was one of the privileges recently granted
                                    Holland.<note n="22" xml:id="d86fn22">See <ref target="#pg_579">pp. 579</ref> ff.</note></p>
                            <p>Please accept [etc.]</p>
                            <closer><signed>P. <hi rend="smallcaps">Forthomme</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>